==English==
===Etymology===
From {{suffix|academic|ian|t2=one skilled in|lang=en}}, partly after {{etyl|fr|en}} {{term|académicien|lang=fr}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/əˌka.dəˈmɪ.ʃn̩/|/ˌa.kə.dəˈmɪ.ʃn̩/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˌæ.kə.dəˈmɪ.ʃn̩/|/əˌkæ.dəˈmɪ.ʃn̩/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ɪʃən|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|now|_|chiefly|_|US|lang=en}} A member (especially a senior one) of the faculty at a [[college]] or [[university]]; an [[academic]]. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}
# A member or follower of an [[academy]], or society for [[promoting]] science, art, or literature, such as the [[French Academy]], or the Royal Academy of Arts. {{defdate|From 17th c.}}
#*'''1890''', {{w|Oscar Wilde}}, ''The Picture of Dorian Gray'', Vintage 2007, p. 9:
#*:‘Well, after I had been in the room about ten minutes, talking to huge overdressed dowagers and tedious '''Academicians''', I suddenly became conscious that some one was looking at me.’

